Availability Zones are physically separate data centers within an Azure region. Each zone has independent power, cooling, and networking, ensuring that failures in one zone do not affect others.

This design provides high availability and fault tolerance for applications.

# Real-Life Example 1:
For example, a critical banking application can be deployed across multiple availability zones. If one zone experiences an outage, the application continues to run from other zones without interruption.

# Real-Life Use Case:
A real-life use case is an online payment system. Any downtime could result in financial loss and customer dissatisfaction. By using availability zones, the system ensures continuous operation even during hardware failures.

# Real-Life Example 2:
Another example is enterprise applications that require 99.99% uptime. Deploying across zones helps meet these strict service-level agreements (SLAs).

Availability zones are essential for building resilient and highly available cloud architectures.
